---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
	title="Drainage"
	description="Simple, low-cost drainage solutions to keep Irish golf courses playable through wet winters - engineering advice from Maurice McKinley BSc CEng MICE."
>
	<section class="section section--tight hero">
		<div class="container">
			<span class="eyebrow">Drainage</span>
			<h1>Simple, low-cost ways to get your drainage working effectively</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				Every winter that a course stays waterlogged is lost revenue, lost play, and a course
				that recovers more slowly in spring. Drainage is the highest-leverage sustainability
				investment most courses can make, and it doesn't have to mean a full rebuild.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<div class="container">
			<div class="grid grid--3">
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Diagnosis first</h3>
					<p>
						Most drainage problems have a specific, identifiable cause, a blocked outfall, a
						failed pipe run, a compacted subsurface layer. Fixing the right thing costs a fraction
						of a speculative, course-wide scheme.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Targeted interventions</h3>
					<p>
						From spot drainage on problem greens and fairways to outfall and ditch clearance,
						the aim is maximum playing-season gain for the lowest capital spend.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Slope &amp; structures</h3>
					<p>
						Where drainage problems are tied to slope stability or built structures, bridges,
						culverts, retaining features, engineering advice covers the constructional and
						procurement side too.
					</p>
					<a href="/services/structures/">See Structures →</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="section section--alt">
		<div class="container">
			<span class="eyebrow">Why it matters more now</span>
			<h2>Wet winters, short seasons</h2>
			<p class="lede">
				Irish courses lose a meaningful share of their playing season to standing water and soft
				ground each winter. Effective drainage is the most direct way to protect revenue and
				course condition, and it compounds with the wider sustainability measures on this site:
				less machinery time spent recovering surfaces, less material lost to erosion, and a
				course that copes better with an increasingly wet climate.
			</p>
			<a href="/sustainability/">See the wider Sustainability programme →</a>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<div class="container" style="display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:1.5rem; align-items:center; justify-content:space-between;">
			<div>
				<h2 style="margin-top:0;">Free introductory consultation</h2>
				<p style="margin-bottom:0; max-width:34rem;">
					A half-day, no-obligation site visit to identify your course's drainage priorities and
					the lowest-cost path to fixing them.
				</p>
			</div>
			<a class="btn btn--primary" href="/contact/">Book a consultation</a>
		</div>
	</section>
</BaseLayout>
